{{Year in Sri Lanka|1994}}

The following lists events that happened during '''[[1994]] in [[Sri Lanka]]'''.

==Incumbents==
*[[Prime Minister of Sri Lanka|Prime Minister]]: [[Dingiri Banda Wijetunga]] (Before 9 November 1994).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/1994%20Presidential.pdf |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090304101347/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/1994%20Presidential.pdf |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2009-03-04 |title=Result of Presidential Election 1994 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |access-date=2015-08-10 |df= }}</ref>
*[[President of Sri Lanka|President]]: [[Chandrika Kumaratunga ]] (After 9 November 1994).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/election/presidential1994.jsp|title=1994 Sri Lanka Presidential Election Results|publisher=LankaNewspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manthree.com/elections/results/?id=6|title=1994 - Presidential Election|publisher=Manthree.com|access-date=2015-08-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130181355/http://www.manthree.com/elections/results/?id=6|archive-date=2010-01-30|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
==Events==
*Prime Minister Chandrika Kumaratunga of the peoples party, wins the 1994 presidential elections following the assassination of [[Ranasinghe Premadasa]]. 
* Many prominent hardliner [[United National Party|UNP]] members are assassinated in 1994.
** [[Gamini Dissanayake]], a former cabinet minister is killed by an [[LTTE]] [[suicide bomber]]. <ref>{{Cite news|title=Q&A: Sri Lanka elections |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/4441820.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=18 November 2005|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Sri Lanka: Searching for a solution |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/412014.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=11 August 1999 |accessdate=10 May 2007}}</ref>
** [[Weerasinghe Mallimarachchi]], another cabinet minister from the [[Colombo district]] is killed from a suicide bombing perpetrated by the LTTE. <ref>{{Cite news|first=V. S. |last=Sambandan |title=Inquiries into Premadasa, Dissanayake killings closed |url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/09/05/stories/2005090507041200.htm |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=5 September 2005 |accessdate=10 August 2015 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=CHRONOLOGY-Assassinations of political figures in Sri Lanka |url=http://today.reuters.co.uk/news/CrisesArticle.aspx?storyId=COL159286&WTmodLoc=World-R5-Alertnet-5 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070424061503/http://today.reuters.co.uk/news/CrisesArticle.aspx?storyId=COL159286&WTmodLoc=World-R5-Alertnet-5 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=24 April 2007 |publisher=[[Reuters UK]] |date=10 November 2006 |accessdate=10 August 2015 }}</ref>   
** [[G. M. Premachandra]], a former chief minister of the UNP is killed in a suicide bombing. <ref>{{Cite news|first=V. S. |last=Sambandan |title=Inquiries into Premadasa, Dissanayake killings closed |url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/09/05/stories/2005090507041200.htm |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=5 September 2005 |accessdate=10 August 2015 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref>
** [[Ossie Abeygunasekara]], one of the UNP MP's was killed in yet another suicide bombing. The LTTE remains the only viable suspect. <ref>{{Cite news|first=V. S. |last=Sambandan |title=Inquiries into Premadasa, Dissanayake killings closed |url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/09/05/stories/2005090507041200.htm |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=5 September 2005 |accessdate=10 August 2015 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref>
