The '''Berkshire Conference of Women Historians Book Prizes''' are awarded each year by the [[Berkshire Conference of Women Historians]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.librarything.com/bookaward/Berkshire+Conference+First+Book+Prize|title=Berkshire Conference First Book Prize {{!}} Book awards {{!}} LibraryThing|website=www.librarything.com|access-date=2017-01-26}}</ref> Nominees must be women normally resident in North America who have published a book in the previous year. One prize recognizes an author's first book that "deals substantially with the history of women, gender, and/or sexuality",<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://berksconference.org/prizes/book-prize-winners/|title=Book Prize Winners {{!}} Berkshire Conference of Women Historians|newspaper=Berkshire Conference of Women Historians|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref> and the other prize recognizes "a first book in any field of history that does not focus on the history of women, gender, and/or sexuality."<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" !Year !Winner !TItle |- |1990 |Jo Burr Margadant |''Madame le Professeur: Women Educators in the Third Republic''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://press.princeton.edu/titles/4670.html|title=Margadant, J.B.: Madame le Professeur: Women Educators in the Third Republic. ([Out of Print])|website=press.princeton.edu|access-date=2017-03-13}}</ref> |- |1990 |[[Laurel Thatcher Ulrich]] |''[[A Midwife's Tale|The Midwife's Tale: The Life of Martha Ballard, Based on her Diary, 1785-1812]]''<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/181591/a-midwifes-tale-by-laurel-thatcher-ulrich/9780679733768|title=A Midwife's Tale by Laurel Thatcher Ulrich {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com|language=en-US}}</ref> |- |1991 |Nancy Leyes Stepan |''"The Hour of Eugenics": Race, Gender and Nation in Latin America''<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/?GCOI=80140100462040|title="The Hour of Eugenics": Race, Gender, and Nation in Latin America|last=Ste