{{other people|Gwyn Williams}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Use British English|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Gwyn A. Williams | image = Gwyn Alf Williams.jpg | caption = Professor Gwyn A. Wiliams | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{birth date|1925|09|30|df=yes}} | birth_name = Gwyn Alfred Williams | birth_place = [[Dowlais]], Wales | death_date = {{death date and age|1995|11|16|1925|09|30|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Cardiff]], Wales | occupation = Professor, Historian, Presenter | genre = | movement = | website = | spouse = | partner = | signature = | nationality = [[British nationality law|British]] | education = | alma_mater = [[Aberystwyth University|University College Wales, Aberystwyth]] | language = English }}
'''Gwyn Alfred "Alf" Williams''' (30 September 1925 – 16 November 1995) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] historian particularly known for his work on [[Antonio Gramsci]] and [[Francisco Goya]] as well as on [[History of Wales|Welsh history]].
== Life == Williams was born in the iron town of [[Dowlais]] situated above the industrial metropolis of [[Merthyr Tydfil]]. He attended the [[Cyfarthfa Castle|Cyfarthfa]] Grammar School and later read History at [[Aberystwyth University|University College Wales, Aberystwyth]]. During [[World War II]], he joined the British Army and fought at [[Invasion of Normandy|Normandy]]. Williams received his doctorate for a dissertation later published as ''Medieval London: from commune to capital''.Gwyn was also a committed Marxist however he became disillusioned with the Russian system following the atrocities committed by [[Stalin]].
==Career== In 1954, Williams was appointed Lecturer in Welsh History at [[Aberystwyth University]] where he worked with another historian of Wales [[David Williams (historian)|David Williams]]. He left Aberystwyth for the [[University of York]] where he was Chair of History from 1965 to 1974. He moved back to Wales in 1974, becoming Professor of History at the [[Cardiff University|University of Wales, Cardiff]], where he stayed until his retirement in 1983. Throughout his career, Williams was known as an exciting lecturer, capable of drawing large crowds from across the university. After his retirement, he continued to write, but he focused more and more on television and film, presenting, with [[Wynford Vaughan-Thomas]], a 13-part series in 1985 by [[ITV Wales & West|HTV]] and [[Channel 4]] on Welsh history entitled ''The Dragon Has Two Tongues''.
Williams was also a supporter of [[Republicanism in the United Kingdom|Republicanism]]; and later a member of [[Plaid Cymru]], he praised the anti-monarchy book ''The Enchanted Glass'' by [[Tom Nairn]].<ref>" We can no longer dodge the central issue of the monarchy.How can we cut free of its tentacles?... Tom Nairn's "quiet republicanism" can start us off". Gwyn A. Williams, Review of ''The Enchanted Glass'' by Tom Nairn. ''Marxism Today'', July 1988. (p. 43)</ref> In 1983 Williams took early retirement from his Chair at Cardiff and began making films with Teliesyn, an independent Welsh broadcasting company based in [[Cardiff]]. He eventually moved from Cardiff to the village of [[Dre-fach Felindre]], in [[Carmarthenshire]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = OBITUARY: Gwyn A. Williams|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/obituary-gwyn-a-williams-1582475.html|website = The Independent|access-date = 2016-01-15|language = en-GB}}</ref>
==Publications== *''Medieval London'', 1963 *''Artisans and Sans-Culottes'', 1968 *''Proletarian Order'', 1975 *''Goya and the Impossible Revolution'', 1976 *''Merthyr Rising'', 1978 *''Madoc: The Making of a Myth'', 1979 *''The Search for Beulah Land: the Welsh and the Atlantic Revolution'', 1980 *''The Welsh in Their History'', 1982 *''When Was Wales?'', 1985 *''Excalibur: the Search for Arthur'', 1994
