{{Infobox academic | name = Ursula Rothe | honorific_suffix = [[PhD]] | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!--For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{tl|birth year and age}} or a similar option.--> | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = | occupation = [[Classicist]] | spouse = | alma_mater = [[University of Manchester]] | influences = | workplaces = [[Open University]], [[University of Sheffield]], [[University of Edinburgh]], [[Reiss-Engelhorn-Museen]] | main_interests = | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = | signature = | signature_size = | footnotes = }}
'''Ursula Rothe''' is an Australian [[classicist]] specialising in the depictions of dress in the northern Roman provinces.<ref name='AJA'>{{cite web |url=https://www.ajaonline.org/author/111 |title=Authors: Ursula Rothe |date=2012 |publisher=[[American Journal of Archaeology]] |accessdate=2017-07-21}}</ref>
==Career== Ursula Rothe gained her doctorate from the [[University of Manchester]] in 2007 and then worked at the [[University of Edinburgh]], first as a teaching associate,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/archaeology/research/dress-and-society/projects/rothe |title=Dr Ursula Rothe |publisher=[[University of Sheffield]] |accessdate=2017-07-21}}</ref> then as a [[Leverhulme Trust|Leverhulme]] postdoctoral research fellow with a project titled 'Dress and identity in the Danube provinces: ideal vs reality'.<ref name='AJA' /> After working at the [[Reiss-Engelhorn-Museen]] in Germany, in 2012 she moved to the [[Open University]] as the [[Baron Lorne Thyssen-Bornemisza|Baron Thyssen]] lecturer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.open.ac.uk/people/ur86 |title=OU People: Ursula Rothe |publisher=[[Open University]] |accessdate=2017-07-20}}</ref> Rothe has been a co-editor of the peer-reviewed journal ''[[Archaeological Textiles Review]]'' since 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atnfriends.com/index_minutes.htm |title=Archaeological Textiles Newsletter/Archaeological Textiles Review |accessdate=2017-07-21}}</ref>
Rothe is also a contributor to [[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] news outlet and has written articles comparing modern immigration policies to the ancient world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theconversation.com/why-hungarys-pm-should-read-up-on-his-history-before-shunning-syrian-refugees-47450 |author1=Rothe, Ursula |title=Why Hungary’s PM should read up on his history before shunning Syrian refugees |date=5 October 2015 |publisher=The Conversation |accessdate=2017-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://theconversation.com/what-the-romans-can-teach-us-on-immigration-and-integration-36391 |author1=Rothe, Ursula |title=What the Romans can teach us on immigration and integration |date=18 February 2015 |publisher=The Conversation |accessdate=2017-07-17}}</ref>
==Selected publications== *Rothe, U. 2009. ''Dress and Cultural Identity in the Rhine-Moselle Region of the Roman Empire'' (BAR International Series S2038). Oxford, [[Archaeopress]]. {{ISBN|978-1-4073-0615-5}} *Rothe, U. 2011. "Der Grabstein der Severina Nutrix aus Köln: eine neue Deutung", ''Germania'' 89, 191-214. *Rothe, U. 2012. "The “Third Way”: Treveran women's dress and the “Gallic Ensemble”", ''[[American Journal of Archaeology]]'' 116(2), 235-252 *Rothe, U. 2014. "Ethnicity in the Roman north-west", in McInerney, J. (ed.) ''A Companion to Ethnicity in the Ancient Mediterranean'', [[Wiley-Blackwell]].{{ISBN|9781444337341}} *Rothe, U. 2013. "Whose fashion? Men, women and Roman culture as reflected in dress in the cities of the Roman north-west", in Hemelrijk, Emily and [[Greg Woolf|Woolf, Greg]] (eds.) ''Women and the Roman City in the Latin West'' (Mnemosyne Supplements, History and Archaeology of Classical Antiquity). [[Brill Publishers|Brill]]. 243-268. {{ISBN|9789004255951}}
